One issue with bloat that is easy to overlook is that the population
contains a range of network sizes and therefore the maximum size of a
network in the population is not necessarily a measure of &quot;bloat&quot;
because other species may contain significantly smaller networks. 
What you probably want to check is that a healthy range is being
maintained rather than simply trying to prevent anything from getting big.

In general, there is good reason to grow networks if fitness is not
going up because the algorithm has no way of knowing what is necessary
to improve. It might need more structure, or it might simply need to
find a better set of weights. Therefore, it is sensible for it to try
both: If you are stagnating, keep growing at one end of the spectrum,
but also don&#39;t lose your little guys in case they turn out sufficient.
In other words, a stagnant population should gradually grow in its
range of sizes, not putting all its eggs in one basket.

For populations that are not stagnant, it makes sense for them to
display less growth in general, because they are succeeding in their
current weight space. I&#39;d guess your more recent experiment is
undergoing periods of stagnation, which would explain why you see more
growth.

I think this idea of having a healthy range of sizes is less prevalent
in GP because GP populations are usually not speciated and therefore
tend to bloat all at once. As soon as someone gets bigger, he starts
mating with others and spreading the extra genes around. Therefore,
GP doesn&#39;t tend to keep a healthy range the way NEAT does. We
actually have built a version of GP-NEAT at EPlex (which has
historical markings and speciation, but with GP trees) that has very
different bloat characteristics than regular GP, as this argument
would suggest. 

In any case, there is still a possibility that things will grow too
fast if the mutation rate for adding structure is too high. However,
that is a simple problem compared to what we see in GP. Also, of
course, some structure that gets added is inevitably unnecessary, and
as you suggest, pruning it out could streamline learning. Several
people on this group have experimented with pruning of various types
(for example, Colin Green, Derek James, and Phillip Tucker) and it
seems to improve performance when done right. But I would guess the
algorithm will not experience a significant pathology even without it.

ken

